505
00:21:52,478 --> 00:21:53,799
and in between them is a phone.

506
00:21:54,639 --> 00:21:57,522
And they start talking, and the phone begins to ring.

507
00:21:58,503 --> 00:22:01,528
And it rings a couple of times before one of the women goes,

508
00:22:01,648 --> 00:22:03,291
oh, well, aren't you going to answer that?

509
00:22:04,135 --> 00:22:06,835
And she says, no, no, no, no, it's probably my son.

510
00:22:06,895 --> 00:22:07,655
I don't want to talk to him.

511
00:22:08,296 --> 00:22:09,636
And they continue talking for a little bit,

512
00:22:09,656 --> 00:22:10,676
and the phone keeps ringing.

513
00:22:11,356 --> 00:22:13,497
And the other woman finally says, you know what?

514
00:22:13,717 --> 00:22:14,797
Maybe you should answer that.

515
00:22:14,837 --> 00:22:15,657
What if he's sick?

516
00:22:15,677 --> 00:22:16,297
What if he's hurt?

517
00:22:16,817 --> 00:22:17,878
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.

518
00:22:18,358 --> 00:22:20,518
You know, we're not really good right now.

519
00:22:20,578 --> 00:22:21,658
She starts talking about the fact

520
00:22:21,678 --> 00:22:24,539
that they got into an argument, and the phone keeps ringing.

521
00:22:24,559 --> 00:22:26,219
And this is pre-answering machines,

522
00:22:26,239 --> 00:22:28,500
which is why that phone is going to keep fucking ringing

523
00:22:28,560 --> 00:22:29,660
until somebody answers it.

524
00:22:30,320 --> 00:22:34,022
And as it's going, the audience, you find yourself kind of

525
00:22:34,503 --> 00:22:36,244
creeping up on the edge of your seat a little bit

526
00:22:36,304 --> 00:22:37,184
and it's agitating you.

527
00:22:37,204 --> 00:22:39,085
You're getting agitated like the other character

528
00:22:39,125 --> 00:22:41,786
because you want her to answer the damn phone.

529
00:22:43,007 --> 00:22:45,309
And they go and go, and what you find out

530
00:22:46,029 --> 00:22:47,991
is that you are getting all of the exposition

531
00:22:48,191 --> 00:22:50,532
about this character's relationship to her son

532
00:22:50,973 --> 00:22:53,274
that normally, if we were lazy,

533
00:22:53,414 --> 00:22:55,235
like a lot of the times I am very lazy,

534
00:22:56,336 --> 00:22:57,917
you would get from Irving the explainer,

535
00:22:58,057 --> 00:22:59,878
who just comes onto the scene and tells you,

536
00:22:59,938 --> 00:23:00,979
here's all the backstory,

537
00:23:01,019 --> 00:23:03,201
this is the sort of situation that I had.

538
00:23:03,261 --> 00:23:05,222
But in that moment, what you got

539
00:23:06,204 --> 00:23:09,847
was a feeling of empathy and a feeling of connection

540
00:23:09,907 --> 00:23:11,809
to a character because you were under stress.

541
00:23:12,029 --> 00:23:14,111
You were taking part in the drama

542
00:23:14,191 --> 00:23:15,612
and finding out about all of this

543
00:23:15,652 --> 00:23:17,313
sort of boring backstory information.

544
00:23:17,874 --> 00:23:20,096
And that stuck with me hugely,

545
00:23:20,456 --> 00:23:21,677
because in what we do,

546
00:23:21,997 --> 00:23:24,760
we can kind of translate that to play versus watch.

547
00:23:25,300 --> 00:23:30,364
And there was so much in the game that we wanted to create in a play experience, right?

548
00:23:30,664 --> 00:23:33,085
But it's really, really expensive.

549
00:23:33,226 --> 00:23:35,567
You have all these sort of fail states and everything that you need to do.

550
00:23:35,647 --> 00:23:41,011
So we did a lot, but there was still a lot more I felt like we could have done.

551
00:23:41,091 --> 00:23:44,293
We just kind of continued to run out of time and said, all right, we have to pull these things out.

552
00:23:44,353 --> 00:23:47,756
But then compensated and then every once in a while some other things got interactive.

553
00:23:48,858 --> 00:23:51,699
So now the combat aspect, really the most important part

554
00:23:51,719 --> 00:23:54,801
of this one, because I continue to love referencing Marvel,

555
00:23:55,821 --> 00:23:59,623
is this idea of Marvel Comics versus Marvel Film.

556
00:24:00,023 --> 00:24:02,484
So Dave Jaffe, when he was pitching the original game

557
00:24:02,524 --> 00:24:04,205
back in 2000, well I came in 2003,

558
00:24:04,725 --> 00:24:06,986
but he was doing it in 2002 before that,

559
00:24:07,767 --> 00:24:09,308
would always talk about God of War

560
00:24:09,528 --> 00:24:11,789
as heavy metal magazine meets...

561
00:24:12,469 --> 00:24:13,910
Clash of the Titans, right?

562
00:24:13,930 --> 00:24:15,872
It's sort of this bombastic comic book,

563
00:24:16,032 --> 00:24:19,334
very mature adult, fantastic sort of experience.

564
00:24:20,115 --> 00:24:22,236
And what we were trying to do

565
00:24:22,316 --> 00:24:25,619
is bring it into the modern era, right?

566
00:24:25,759 --> 00:24:27,040
And the games that we were playing,

567
00:24:27,060 --> 00:24:28,521
the games that are exciting us of today,

568
00:24:29,101 --> 00:24:30,162
we wanted to bring this in there.

569
00:24:30,262 --> 00:24:32,284
We were looking at the way that Marvel

570
00:24:32,304 --> 00:24:34,826
would translate comic books into film, right?

571
00:24:34,866 --> 00:24:37,307
My mom would not read a Thor comic.

572
00:24:38,028 --> 00:24:39,569
But she'd be damn sure she's gonna go see

573
00:24:39,649 --> 00:24:41,731
Chris Hemsworth as Thor, right?

574
00:24:42,777 --> 00:24:45,298
So I was like, as long as I cast Chris, I'm good, right?

575
00:24:45,318 --> 00:24:46,098
My mom will play the game.

576
00:24:47,379 --> 00:24:49,680
But that transition really showed

577
00:24:49,720 --> 00:24:51,501
that you can take something fantastic

578
00:24:51,801 --> 00:24:54,362
and bring it and expand the audience

579
00:24:54,762 --> 00:24:57,324
and get them to connect to the work that you're doing.

580
00:24:57,624 --> 00:25:01,125
And the context in the drama was also another important thing

581
00:25:01,145 --> 00:25:01,486
of saying.

582
00:25:02,166 --> 00:25:04,147
A lot of us make games that have combat in them.

583
00:25:04,367 --> 00:25:04,967
You know, it's fun.

584
00:25:05,428 --> 00:25:08,029
It's very sort of frenetic and exciting

585
00:25:08,309 --> 00:25:09,249
to have combat in your game,

586
00:25:09,289 --> 00:25:11,450
but a lot of the times you don't have any context

587
00:25:11,670 --> 00:25:14,992
of this combat within the drama of your game, right?

588
00:25:15,032 --> 00:25:17,973
To actually feel like, oh, the combat means something

589
00:25:18,014 --> 00:25:20,415
in the overall goal, and coming up with that simple goal,

590
00:25:20,655 --> 00:25:22,616
at this time I had known that we were going to

591
00:25:22,996 --> 00:25:24,357
take the ashes to the top of the mountain.

592
00:25:24,697 --> 00:25:26,838
Everything started to feed into this goal that was simple.

593
00:25:27,438 --> 00:25:29,322
Everybody understood it very quickly in the game,

594
00:25:29,522 --> 00:25:31,526
and you were able to feel like each one of these fights

595
00:25:31,626 --> 00:25:33,229
meant something even more.

596
00:25:33,390 --> 00:25:34,932
And to a certain degree, we succeeded.

597
00:25:34,972 --> 00:25:38,098
Certain degrees, we can continue to do better in all of that.

598
00:25:39,547 --> 00:25:46,332
The exploration was a whole new thing for this game because I wanted it to be so much bigger than anything that we had done.

599
00:25:47,052 --> 00:25:52,255
And at the time when I was pitching this, talking about the mechanics that would encourage discovery and exploration,

600
00:25:52,936 --> 00:25:55,658
we didn't have those mechanics. We were still figuring a lot of stuff out.

601
00:25:55,678 --> 00:25:58,079
In fact, the engine wasn't completely ready.

602
00:25:58,599 --> 00:26:02,542
A lot of things were like Lego pieces all over the floor, and I'm trying to...

603
00:26:02,882 --> 00:26:05,603
hey, we need to come up with new verbs of how to make puzzles.

604
00:26:05,703 --> 00:26:07,164
And it's like, OK, but how?

605
00:26:07,244 --> 00:26:09,085
We can't even build anything in the engine right now.

606
00:26:09,525 --> 00:26:10,646
So that was very stressful.

607
00:26:11,086 --> 00:26:13,567
This time, especially when we were doing exploration,

608
00:26:13,587 --> 00:26:15,548
was one of the more stressful.

609
00:26:15,568 --> 00:26:17,548
In fact, honestly, the whole damn project was stressful.

610
00:26:17,568 --> 00:26:20,310
But there was a tremendous amount, for me,

611
00:26:20,430 --> 00:26:23,391
of this doubt in wondering, are we

612
00:26:23,411 --> 00:26:25,292
going to be able to finish any of this stuff?

613
00:26:25,332 --> 00:26:27,513
Because there is just so much to get done.

614
00:26:29,372 --> 00:26:32,333
And the character growth, everything feeding into that one,

615
00:26:32,373 --> 00:26:35,214
I had really started to cement what this meant,

616
00:26:35,554 --> 00:26:37,294
continue to say teach, right?

617
00:26:37,474 --> 00:26:39,595
Even though I had no idea how teaching

618
00:26:39,635 --> 00:26:41,056
was gonna take place in the game,

619
00:26:41,416 --> 00:26:42,516
I had that fallback of like, okay,

620
00:26:42,536 --> 00:26:43,957
well, upgrading is kind of like teaching.

621
00:26:43,977 --> 00:26:45,257
Your kid gets better throughout the game.

622
00:26:45,677 --> 00:26:47,358
But thankfully, working with the team,

623
00:26:47,398 --> 00:26:49,600
they end up kind of contributing so many different ideas

624
00:26:49,640 --> 00:26:52,582
that make that initial kernel of something a lot better.

625
00:26:53,002 --> 00:26:55,724
But it was important to actually see these characters change,

626
00:26:56,125 --> 00:26:57,706
not just in their dramatic art,

627
00:26:57,746 --> 00:26:59,847
but in their sort of visual as well as their play,

628
00:27:00,268 --> 00:27:03,070
so that it actually feels like what you're doing

629
00:27:03,590 --> 00:27:06,932
is growing with these characters, experiencing their lives.

630
00:27:07,840 --> 00:27:10,064
So the pitching of all this stuff,

631
00:27:10,204 --> 00:27:13,248
I would be pitching all the way through the end of the project.

632
00:27:13,308 --> 00:27:15,612
It would just continue ad nauseum.

633
00:27:15,772 --> 00:27:16,593
That's really all you do.

634
00:27:16,633 --> 00:27:19,878
It's like selling cars to the team every day, over and over.

635
00:27:19,938 --> 00:27:21,160
And nobody buys a damn car.

636
00:27:21,180 --> 00:27:22,241
That's what's fucked up about it.

637
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,242
But the doubt also continues throughout all

638
00:27:27,362 --> 00:27:28,183
of this experience.

639
00:27:28,243 --> 00:27:31,865
And I know that everybody in here who makes games,

640
00:27:32,325 --> 00:27:34,467
we all experience failure every day.

641
00:27:35,087 --> 00:27:37,969
We all experience doubt every four minutes.

642
00:27:38,769 --> 00:27:39,390
It's science, man.

643
00:27:39,570 --> 00:27:40,310
I totally looked that up.

644
00:27:40,811 --> 00:27:41,591
It's every four minutes.

645
00:27:41,892 --> 00:27:43,453
So what I'm gonna do is I'm just gonna tell a story now

646
00:27:43,493 --> 00:27:45,735
because I fucking hate PowerPoint presentations.

647
00:27:46,535 --> 00:27:49,738
And I'm gonna talk about the E3 2016 demo.

648
00:27:50,358 --> 00:27:56,483
So this story encapsulates so many versions of doubt,

649
00:27:56,803 --> 00:28:01,247
so many areas of failure that we experienced on this project

650
00:28:01,767 --> 00:28:05,030
and is kind of, for me, one of the most interesting

651
00:28:05,930 --> 00:28:07,151
clips of game development.

652
00:28:07,652 --> 00:28:12,095
So initially, we knew that we were gonna do a reveal.

653
00:28:12,795 --> 00:28:15,897
We had honed in on E3 2016 as being the time

654
00:28:15,937 --> 00:28:17,178
we were gonna do that reveal.

655
00:28:18,139 --> 00:28:20,861
But I had no clue what it was gonna be.

656
00:28:20,941 --> 00:28:22,142
Was it just gonna be a logo?

657
00:28:22,722 --> 00:28:26,404
Were we just gonna show a quick clip of the game?

658
00:28:26,424 --> 00:28:29,827
Were we gonna try to show a cut video together, right?

659
00:28:29,867 --> 00:28:31,988
I was gonna try to sell people on a no-cut camera

660
00:28:32,068 --> 00:28:33,289
and cut a bunch of shots together.

661
00:28:33,329 --> 00:28:33,950
That wasn't gonna work.

662
00:28:34,830 --> 00:28:36,991
Or were we gonna actually try to do a demo,

663
00:28:37,051 --> 00:28:39,432
which was insane, right?

664
00:28:39,552 --> 00:28:40,872
Like the first time you're gonna reveal your game

665
00:28:40,892 --> 00:28:42,513
and you really don't have all the pieces together

666
00:28:42,553 --> 00:28:43,093
and what are you gonna do?

667
00:28:43,113 --> 00:28:45,814
You're gonna actually play a demo live on stage?

668
00:28:46,434 --> 00:28:47,474
I totally chose that one,

669
00:28:47,834 --> 00:28:51,676
because the thing was far away.

670
00:28:52,156 --> 00:28:53,736
It was like nine or 10 months away.

671
00:28:53,796 --> 00:28:55,677
So I was like, yeah, let's do the hardest thing.

672
00:28:55,697 --> 00:28:57,598
And I feel like I do that all the time,

673
00:28:57,898 --> 00:28:59,518
which is I agree to do something really hard

674
00:28:59,538 --> 00:29:01,099
and then write when it comes time to do it.

675
00:29:01,727 --> 00:29:03,508
it all, all my chickens go home to Ruth.

676
00:29:03,548 --> 00:29:04,789
I'm like, what the hell, man?

677
00:29:05,230 --> 00:29:06,191
Why did I agree to this?

678
00:29:06,831 --> 00:29:09,714
So I started writing up different demo ideas,

679
00:29:09,774 --> 00:29:12,016
just really jotting stuff down quickly.

680
00:29:13,037 --> 00:29:14,418
And at the time, we had not figured out

681
00:29:14,438 --> 00:29:15,119
the beginning of the game.

682
00:29:15,999 --> 00:29:17,441
I had written the short story back then,

683
00:29:17,481 --> 00:29:18,422
but we had not settled on,

684
00:29:18,462 --> 00:29:19,703
hey, that's gonna be the beginning of the game.

685
00:29:19,743 --> 00:29:22,425
We were focusing a lot on the middle section of the game,

686
00:29:22,445 --> 00:29:25,087
so some stuff in the mountain, if you've all played the game.

687
00:29:25,568 --> 00:29:27,308
you'll understand this part, inside the mountain.

688
00:29:28,048 --> 00:29:29,449
And so I said, oh, you know what, I'm gonna do that.

689
00:29:29,529 --> 00:29:31,729
I'm gonna write a demo up, it'll be inside the mountain.

690
00:29:32,889 --> 00:29:35,530
It'll end at the elevator, kind of going up,

691
00:29:36,330 --> 00:29:39,350
and there'll be a big scary monster reveal at the end

692
00:29:39,370 --> 00:29:41,131
that screams, and then you go to black

693
00:29:41,211 --> 00:29:42,291
all fucking dramatically.

694
00:29:43,511 --> 00:29:44,491
It's so cheesy.

695
00:29:45,731 --> 00:29:47,432
But I thought it was really great.

696
00:29:47,612 --> 00:29:49,312
There was a part of me that was saying,

697
00:29:49,332 --> 00:29:51,092
mm, this isn't so good.

698
00:29:51,152 --> 00:29:52,693
So I was sending it to people on the team.

699
00:29:53,593 --> 00:29:55,194
And I think they were just being nice, and they were like,

700
00:29:55,214 --> 00:29:56,294
oh, yeah, sure, that's cool.

701
00:29:57,415 --> 00:29:58,956
Oh, sure, that's cool is not the response

702
00:29:58,996 --> 00:30:00,917
you want when you send somebody a demo writer.

703
00:30:00,937 --> 00:30:01,857
You want them to be like, yeah.

704
00:30:02,238 --> 00:30:06,620
So I got some notes from people and sort of settled on it.

705
00:30:06,660 --> 00:30:08,141
We were like, all right, this is good.

706
00:30:08,341 --> 00:30:10,342
But there's always something inside of me that was saying,

707
00:30:10,362 --> 00:30:11,463
I don't think this is very good.

708
00:30:11,903 --> 00:30:14,204
But to be honest, there is always

709
00:30:14,384 --> 00:30:16,686
something inside of me that is saying, this is no good,

710
00:30:16,786 --> 00:30:17,206
and you suck.

711
00:30:18,106 --> 00:30:19,987
So I was like, all right, whatever, I'm going to ignore that.

712
00:30:20,647 --> 00:30:22,909
And we were going to have the events people,

713
00:30:22,929 --> 00:30:24,729
the PR people, and the marketing people

714
00:30:24,850 --> 00:30:26,210
all coming down to the studio,

715
00:30:26,310 --> 00:30:27,511
and I was going to do the pitch for them.

716
00:30:28,711 --> 00:30:30,192
And it's kind of the same thing as this,

717
00:30:30,212 --> 00:30:32,253
where you just get up and you wave your arms around a lot

718
00:30:32,293 --> 00:30:33,274
because you're asking for money,

719
00:30:34,114 --> 00:30:35,495
and you draw on the board,

720
00:30:35,615 --> 00:30:38,856
and it looks really great in photos, right?

721
00:30:39,437 --> 00:30:41,918
So I get in, I start doing the pitch,

722
00:30:42,238 --> 00:30:44,059
and I realize like five minutes in,

723
00:30:45,198 --> 00:30:47,059
that everybody's starting to fidget in their seats.

724
00:30:47,740 --> 00:30:49,361
Some people are checking their phone.

725
00:30:49,681 --> 00:30:50,982
I'm really losing them.

726
00:30:51,463 --> 00:30:52,423
And I start to speak louder

727
00:30:52,484 --> 00:30:54,785
because that totally makes the audience come back.

728
00:30:56,547 --> 00:30:57,467
And that did not work.

729
00:30:58,048 --> 00:31:00,149
And about halfway through the pitch, I realized.

730
00:31:01,496 --> 00:31:02,837
this is absolute crap.

731
00:31:03,518 --> 00:31:05,820
And you were right to think it was crap, because it's crap.

732
00:31:06,060 --> 00:31:07,281
But I'm still giving the pitch.

733
00:31:07,701 --> 00:31:11,584
So in my mind, I'm starting to think of ways to eject.

734
00:31:11,985 --> 00:31:13,586
Like, OK, what can I do here?

735
00:31:13,626 --> 00:31:14,867
I need to come up with a better solution.

736
00:31:14,907 --> 00:31:15,668
This is not working.

737
00:31:15,988 --> 00:31:18,590
And I start having a few ideas of potentially

738
00:31:18,610 --> 00:31:20,972
the beginning of the game, a few visual ideas that are coming up

739
00:31:21,012 --> 00:31:22,714
while I'm just running on autopilot on the pitch,

740
00:31:22,734 --> 00:31:24,035
because I figure, why try?

741
00:31:24,055 --> 00:31:25,136
It sucks.

742
00:31:25,516 --> 00:31:26,197
They're not having fun.

743
00:31:26,217 --> 00:31:28,258
I get all the way to the end of the pitch,

744
00:31:28,278 --> 00:31:29,920
and everybody's, yeah, cool.

745
00:31:30,060 --> 00:31:30,260
All right.

746
00:31:30,540 --> 00:31:30,660
Yeah.

747
00:31:30,820 --> 00:31:32,301
Nobody outright says it sucks.

748
00:31:33,782 --> 00:31:35,263
That's usually only on the development side.

749
00:31:35,303 --> 00:31:36,524
We're very honest with each other,

750
00:31:36,584 --> 00:31:38,245
but people in the PR and marketing groups,

751
00:31:38,265 --> 00:31:39,926
they're all very nice, they're very good people.

752
00:31:40,446 --> 00:31:43,128
And they will just say it sucks when they leave the room,

753
00:31:43,388 --> 00:31:44,168
or when you leave the room.

754
00:31:45,489 --> 00:31:47,290
So I was like, all right, thank you, everybody.

755
00:31:48,351 --> 00:31:50,592
I left the room, and I think somebody had talked

756
00:31:50,612 --> 00:31:52,313
to Shannon immediately afterwards and said,

757
00:31:52,977 --> 00:31:54,619
Yikes, that was bad.

758
00:31:54,639 --> 00:31:57,722
You know, it's not terrible, it's just not that exciting.

